Cruz Azul]]/[[Pepsi]]/[[Telmex]]\n|-\n|2002\u201304\n|rowspan=8| [[Umbro]]\n| [[Cemento Cruz Azul]]/[[Pepsi]]/[[Telmex]]\n|-\n|2004\u201308\n| [[Cemento Cruz Azul]]/[[Coca-Cola]]/[[Telcel]]\n|-\n|2008\u201309\n| [[Cemento Cruz Azul]]/[[Coca-Cola]]/[[Telcel]]/[[Sony]]\n|-\n|2009\u201310\n| [[Cemento Cruz Azul]]/[[Powerade]]/[[Telcel]]/[[Sony]]\n|-\n|2010\u201311\n| [[Cemento Cruz Azul]]/[[Coca-Cola]]/[[Telcel]]\n|-\n|2011\u201312\n| [[Cemento Cruz Azul]]/[[Coca-Cola]]/[[Telcel]]/[[Cuauht\u00e9moc Moctezuma Brewery#Tecate|Tecate]]/[[Volaris]]\n|-\n|2012\u201313\n| [[Cemento Cruz Azul]]/[[Coca-Cola]]/[[Telcel]]/[[Cuauht\u00e9moc Moctezuma Brewery#Tecate|Tecate]]/[[Volaris]]\n|-\n|2013\u201314\n| [[Cemento Cruz Azul]]/[[Coca-Cola]]/[[Telcel]]/[[Cuauht\u00e9moc Moctezuma Brewery#Tecate|Tecate]]/[[Scotiabank]]\n|-\n|2014\u201317\n|rowspan=3| [[Under Armour]]\n| [[Cemento Cruz Azul]]/[[Pascual Boing|Boing!]]/[[Scotiabank]]/[[Telcel]]/[[Cuauht\u00e9moc Moctezuma Brewery#Tecate|Tecate]]\n|-\n|2017\u20132018\n| [[Cemento Cruz Azul]]/[[Scotiabank]]/[[Telcel]]/[[Cuauht\u00e9moc Moctezuma Brewery#Tecate|Tecate]]\n|-\n|2018\n|| [[Cemento Cruz Azul]]/Caliente\n|-\n|2019\u2013\n|[[Joma]]\n||[[Cemento Cruz Azul]]\n|}\n\n==Honors==\n\n===Domestic===\n*'''[[Mexican Primera Divisi\u00f3n]]/[[Liga MX]]: 8'''\n::[[1968\u201369 Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico|1968\u201369]], [[1970 Mexican Primera Divisi\u00f3n season|1970]], [[1971\u201372 Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico|1971\u201372]], [[1972\u201373 Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico|1972\u201373]], [[1973\u201374 Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico|1973\u201374]], [[1978\u201379 Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico|1978\u201379]], [[1979\u201380 Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico|1979\u201380]], [[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico Invierno 1997|Invierno 1997]]\n\n*'''[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico]]/[[Ascenso MX]]: 1'''\n::1963\u201364\n\n*'''[[Copa MX|Copa M\u00e9xico/Copa MX]]: 4'''\n::1968\u201369, 1996\u201397, [[Clausura 2013 Copa MX|Clausura 2013]], [[Apertura 2018 Copa MX|Apertura 2018]]\n\n*'''[[Campe\u00f3n de Campeones]]: 2'''\n::1968\u201369, 1973\u201374\n\n*'''[[Campeonisimo]]: 1'''\n::1969\n\n*'''[[Supercopa MX]]: 1'''\n::[[2019 Supercopa MX|2019]]\n\n===International===\n\n*'''[[CONCACAF Champions League]]: 6'''\n::[[1969 CONCACAF Champions' Cup|1969]], [[1970 CONCACAF Champions' Cup|1970]], [[1971 CONCACAF Champions' Cup|1971]], [[1996 CONCACAF Champions' Cup|1996]], [[1997 CONCACAF Champions' Cup|1997]], [[2013\u201314 CONCACAF Champions League|2013\u201314]]\n*'''[[Leagues Cup]]: 1'''\n::[[2019 Leagues Cup|2019]]\n\n==Nicknames==\n\n[[File:Polarhase 1 1997-08-04.jpg|thumb|200px|right|The [[hare]] is the animal that is used to represent the team.]]\nCruz Azul has a rich variety of nicknames over its history, listed chronologically:\n\n* Cementeros (cement workers): As a result of affiliation with Cruz Azul Cement, the first name refers directly to the employees of the company, as the team originally was formed with them. Over the years, the concept is extended not only to those who worked in the cooperative, but the construction workers in general.\n* Liebres ([[hares]]): When the team was promoted to the Primera Divisi\u00f3n in the mid-1960s, the club played a fast and physical game.  These characteristics, coupled with their mostly white uniforms, led fans to compare the players of those years with the hares which abound in the town.  The nickname took hold, and an [[Anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] hare is often used as a mascot and icon to represent Cruz Azul. While some modern fans believe that the mascot is a rabbit, the club's board has officially declared that it is a hare.\n* La M\u00e1quina (the machine, the [[locomotive]]): This nickname is fed by several sources of inspiration.  One is based on a railway that brought the cement from the Cruz Azul plant, in the former village of Jasso (south of [[Tula de Allende]]), to Mexico City. After moving to Mexico City, Cruz Azul was the most dominant club in Mexico during the 1970s, reinforcing the nickname as a comparison to the image of a locomotive sweeping through their opponents. The name may have been borrowed from the similarly nicknamed [[History of Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate#1940s: \"La M\u00e1quina\"|River Plate]] club that motored through its opponents in the [[Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n]] in the 1940s. It has been suggested that reporter Rugama Angel Fernandez was the first to publish an article with the name La M\u00e1quina for Cruz Azul. The nickname has some variations, including The Celestial Machine, The Blue Machine and The Cement Machine.\n\n==The Cheerleaders (Las Celestes)==\nThe club has its official cheerleading club, which were included as part of the institution since 2004, since then, act as [[cheerleader]]s in the proceedings of the club in their home games before and at halftime.\nFrom its appearance of \"Las Celestes\" have formed part of the tradition of the club. And the only Mexican team that has as part of their group at their official cheerleaders.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.resultados-futbol.com/porristas-celestes-rf_36441.jpg |title=Resultados-futbol.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-10}}</ref>\n\n==Popularity and rivalries==\n\n===Popularity===\nSince its inception, the team had supporters, mainly workers of the cement. After promotion to the Primera Divisi\u00f3n in the 1960s, more people began to follow the team. In the 1970s when the team managed six of their eight titles even more people joined the group of supporters of the team, until now that in this 21st century according to various surveys{{which|date=May 2013}} is the third team with the most supporters in Mexico,{{Citation needed|date=May 2013}} behind the Club Guadalajara and Am\u00e9rica respectively, above the club UNAM.\n\n<gallery widths=\"80pxpx\" heights=\"100px\" perrow=\"7\" caption=\"Popularity\">\nFile:Sangreazul inconcachampions.jpg|\"La Sangre\" in Concachampions.\nFile:CruzAzulFanClubDF.JPG|A store for fans of Cruz Azul.\nFile:Sangreaz.jpg|\"La Sangre\" Logo.\n</gallery>\n\n===Rivalries===\nNational Rivalries:\n* Main Rivalry: the \"[[Cl\u00e1sico Joven]]\"  vs. Club Am\u00e9rica.\n\n==Records==\n[[File:Azteca 008.png|thumb|230px|right|Cruz Azul game against America in the Azteca Stadium]]\n* Cruz Azul has the distinction of being the only Mexican football club to win the North American treble&nbsp;\u2013 winning the League, Mexican, and North American championships in 1997.\n* Along with Club America, It is the Mexican club with the most titles at international level (6 titles in the Copa de Campeones de CONCACAF, plus a runner-Inter's Cup in 1972 and another in the Copa Libertadores de America in 2001).\n* Along with Club America, Mexican Club with most titles in the Copa de Campeones de CONCACAF, with 6.\n* Holds the record for most consecutive wins in the history of the Primera Divisi\u00f3n: 10 wins in the 1971\u201372 season.\n* The Mexican team with the highest number of plays playoffs (43), counting rounds of reclassification.\n* It is the first Mexican team in a final crown with a \"golden goal\" (1997).\n* It is the team that has played league final (14) and lost (8), besides being the second most paradoxically end wins (6) (along with Deportivo Toluca and Pumas de la UNAM).\n* It is the only team that thrashed in the final's Am\u00e9rica to win the league title (4 goals to 1) in the 1971\u20131972 season.\n* It is one of the three teams in the history of the Primera Divisi\u00f3n have been three-time league (succeeding in 1971\u20131972,1972\u20131973 and 1973\u20131974), the other two teams are Am\u00e9rica who did a decade later and the Club Deportivo Guadalajara.\n* It is the youngest team to be champions and cup, reached only five years after his rise in the 1968\u20131969 season.\n* It is the youngest team in making seven league titles. (Only in 15 years in Mexico's Primera Divisi\u00f3n.)\n\n==Club statistics and records==\n\n===Professional Era (1964 \u2013 )===\n*'''''Seasons in [[Mexican Primera Divisi\u00f3n|Primera Divisi\u00f3n]]:''''' 62\n*'''''Seasons in [[Liga de Ascenso|2nd Division o Primera \"A\"]]:''''' 4.\n*'''Playoff for the title:''' 44\n*'''Final for the title:''' 19 (68\u201369, 69\u201370, M\u00c9X 70, 71\u201372, 72\u201373, 73\u201374, 78\u201379, 79\u201380, 80\u201381, 86\u201387, 88\u201389, 94\u201395, Inv. 97, Inv. 99, Clau. 08, Aper. 08, Aper. 09, Clau. 13, Aper. 18)\n*'''1st place:''' 13\n*'''Relegated to [[Liga de Ascenso|2nd Division o Primera \"A\"]]:''' 0\n*'''Promotion to the 1st Div:''' 1 (1963\u201364)\n*'''Final position more repeated:''' 1st (13 times)\n*'''''Best place in [[Mexican Primera Divisi\u00f3n|Primera Divisi\u00f3n]]:'''''\n** In long tournaments: 1st (1968/1969, Mexico 1970, 1971/1972, 1972/1973, 1973/1974, 1978/1979, 1995/1996)\n** In short tournaments: 1st (Winter 1998, Winter 2000, Apertura 2006, Apertura 2010, Clausura 2014, Apertura 2018)\n*''''' Worse place in [[Mexican Primera Divisi\u00f3n|Primera Divisi\u00f3n]]:'''''\n** In long tournaments: 18th of 20 teams: 1989\u201390\n** In short tournaments: 18th of 18 teams: Clausura 2009\n*''''' Highest score achieved :'''''\n** The national tournament: 8\u20132 vs. [[Toros Neza]] (1993\u201394).\n** In international tournaments: 12\u20132 against the {{flagicon|Belize}} [[Hankook Verdes|Leslie Verdes]] in [[1988 CONCACAF Champions' Cup]] and 11\u20130 against the {{flagicon|USA}} [[Seattle Sounders (1994\u20132008)|Seattle Sounders]] in the [[1996 CONCACAF Champions' Cup]]\n*''''' Highest score against:'''''\n** The national tournament: 0\u20135 against Am\u00e9rica (1981\u201382).\n** In international tournaments: 1\u20136 against the {{flagicon|Uruguay}} [[Centro Atl\u00e9tico F\u00e9nix|F\u00e9nix]] in the [[2003 Copa Libertadores]]\n*''''' Most points in a season :'''''\n** In long tournaments: 57 (1978\u201379)\n** In short tournaments: 40 ([[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico Invierno 1998|Invierno 1998]])\n*''''' Longest streak of games without losing :'''''\n** 19 (round 18 from semifinal round of (1973\u201374).\n*'''Longest undefeated streak at home'''\n** 47 (1978\u20131980) (Mexican football record)\n*'''''Most goals scored in a season :'''''\n** In long tournaments: 91 (1994\u201395).\n** In short tournaments: 41 ([[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico Invierno 1998|Invierno 1998]]).\n*'''Most wins in a season:''' 22, Season (1971\u201372)\n*'''Most draws in a season:''' 17, (1989\u201390)\n*'''Most defeats in a season:''' 13, (1982\u201383) and (1989\u201390)\n*'''Consecutive wins in a season:''' 11, (1979\u201380) (Mexican football record)\n*'''More games without conceding:''' 5, season (1975\u201376), and (1983\u201384)\n*'''Most consecutive wins:''' 10, (1971\u201372) (Mexican football record)\n*'''Most consecutive draws''': 5, (1973\u201374)\n*'''Most consecutive games without a win:''' 11, (1965\u201366)\n*'''Fewest wins in a season:''' 2, [[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico Clausura 2009|Clausura 2009]]\n*'''Fewest draws in a season:''' 0, [[2009\u201310 Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico season|Apertura 2009]]\n*'''Fewest defeats in one season:''' 1, [[1985\u201386 Mexican Primera Divisi\u00f3n season#Prode-1985|PRODE 85]], [[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico Invierno 1998|Invierno 1998]]\n*'''Player with the most goals in a season:''' {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Carlos Hermosillo]] with 35 in (1994\u201395)\n*'''Most titles won'''\n** Head Coach: {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Ra\u00fal C\u00e1rdenas]]\n***11 titles: [[Liga MX|Primera Divisi\u00f3n]] (1968\u201369, M\u00e9xico 1970, 1971\u201372, 1972\u201373, 1973\u201374), [[Copa M\u00e9xico]] (1968\u201369), [[Campeon de Campeones]] (1968\u201369, 1973\u201374), [[CONCACAF Champions' Cup]] (1969, 1970, 1971)\n** Player: {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[:es:Fernando Bustos|Fernando Bustos]]\n***13 titles: [[Liga MX|Primera Divisi\u00f3n]] (1968\u201369, M\u00e9xico 1970, 1971\u201372, 1972\u201373, 1973\u201374, 1978\u201379), [[Ascenso MX|Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] (1963\u201364), [[Copa M\u00e9xico]] (1968\u201369), [[Campeon de Campeones]] (1968\u201369, 1973\u201374), [[CONCACAF Champions' Cup]] (1969, 1970, 1971)\n\n==Stadium==\n[[File:Estadio Azteca1706p2.jpg|300px|thumb|[[Estadio Azteca]]]]\n[[File:15-07-2015 Plaza M\u00e9xico y Estadio Azul, Mexico-RalfR-WMA 0974.jpg|300px|thumb|[[Estadio Azul]]]]\n{{See also|Estadio Azteca|Estadio Azul|Nuevo Estadio Azul}}\n\nThe team currently plays in the [[Estadio Azteca]] in [[Mexico City]]. Cruz Azul's training facilities are named \"La Noria\", which are located in [[Xochimilco]].\n\nThe team returned to the [[Estadio Azteca]] in the Apertura 2018 season after spending 22 years at [[Estadio Azul]], which has been slated to be demolished. The team has indicated that it intends to build [[Nuevo Estadio Azul|a new stadium]], but solid plans such as location have not materialized.<ref>http://stadiumdb.com/news/2018/02/mexico_city_cruz_azul_still_not_settled_for_stadium_location</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"100px\" heights=\"100px\" perrow=\"6\" caption=\"Stadium\">\nFile:CrAzulStadium1.JPG|Seen from a side street\nFile:Estadio Azul from the air.jpg|Estadio Azul from the air\nFile:ViewInsideCrAzulDF.JPG|View inside the Estadio Azul\n</gallery>\n\n==Top Goalscorers==\n{| class=\"sortable\" border=1 width=90% cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%; text-align: left;\"\n|- align=center bgcolor=Blue style=\"color:white;\"\n!#\n!Name\n!LIG\n!CUP\n!SPC\n!CON\n!LIB\n!FWC\n!INT\n!RCF\n!Total\n|-align=center\n| 1 || {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Carlos Hermosillo]] || 168 || 19 || \u2013 || 10 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 ||- || '''197'''\n|-align=center\n| 2 || {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[Horacio L\u00f3pez Salgado]] || 133 || ? || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 ||- || '''133'''\n|-al